Hi there! I'd be happy to help you understand the difference between "this" and "super" keywords in Java.

First, let's start with the basics. In Java, "this" refers to the current object or instance that is being referred to. It is used to indicate that a method or field belongs to the current object, rather than to some other object or class.

On the other hand, "super" refers to the immediate parent class or object of the current object. It is used to access members of the parent class, such as methods or fields, from a subclass.

Now, let me give you an example to illustrate the difference between "this" and "super". Imagine you have two classes, Animal and Mammal, with the following code:
```
class Animal {
    void eat() {
        System.out.println("Eating...");
    }
}

class Mammal extends Animal {
    @Override
    void eat() {
        System.out.println("Mammals eat...");
    }
}
```
In this example, "Mammal" is a subclass of "Animal". If we create an instance of the Mammal class and call its "eat()" method, the following code will be executed:
```
Mammal mammal = new Mammal();
mammal.eat(); // Output: "Mammals eat..."
```
Here, "super" would refer to the "Animal" class, so we can use "super.eat()" to call the "eat()" method of the parent class. However, we don't need to use "super" in this case because the method is already overridden in the Mammal class.

Now, if we were to create an instance of the Animal class and call its "eat()" method, the following code would be executed:
```
Animal animal = new Animal();
animal.eat(); // Output: "Eating..."
```
Here, "this" would refer to the Animal object, so we can use "this.eat()" to call the "eat()" method of the current object.

In summary, "this" refers to the current object, while "super" refers to the immediate parent class or object. The difference between "this" and "super" lies in their scope and purpose. "This" is used to access members of the current object, while "super" is used to access members of the parent class.

I hope this explanation helps you understand the difference between "this" and "super" keywords in Java! Do you have any more questions or queries?

