In object-oriented programming, the `this` keyword refers to the current instance of a class, while the `super` keyword refers to the parent class or object.

Using `this`, a method can access and modify the properties of the current object, and call other methods of the same object. For example:

```java
class Example {
  int x = 10;

  void incrementX() {
    this.x = this.x + 1;
  }
}
```
In the above code, `this.x` refers to the `x` property of the current object, and `this` is used to call the `incrementX()` method of the same object.

Using `super`, a method can access and modify the properties and methods of the parent class or object. For example:

```java
class Parent {
  int x = 10;

  void printX() {
    System.out.println(x);
  }
}

class Child extends Parent {
  void incrementX() {
    super.x = super.x + 1;
  }
}
```
In the above code, `super.x` refers to the `x` property of the Parent class, and `super` is used to call the `printX()` method of the Parent class.

